{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537020"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:12:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15879"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.17,0.1,0.17,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8570"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62991"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8570"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48442"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"1877"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"50088"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62991"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department by her parents with a two-week history of behavioural changes. She has become increasingly paranoid, believing her university professors are plotting against her. She has also experienced auditory hallucinations. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a university student and lives at home. She does not use recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears agitated. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She has oro-facial dyskinesia and choreiform movements of her arms. Her Glasgow Coma Scale score is 14/15 (confused). Neurological examination reveals generalised hyperreflexia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute schizophrenia","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Substance-induced psychosis","First episode psychosis","Anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis young woman presents with psychiatric symptoms that could initially suggest a primary psychotic disorder. However, several features point towards \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-NMDA receptor encephalitis\u003C/strong\u003E as the most likely diagnosis. These include the presence of movement disorders (oro-facial dyskinesia and choreiform movements), autonomic instability (tachycardia, hypertension), fever, and decreased level of consciousness. The combination of psychiatric symptoms with these neurological features is characteristic of anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst episode psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E would not typically present with movement disorders, autonomic instability, or altered consciousness. While psychosis can present with agitation and paranoid delusions, the neurological features in this case suggest an organic cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeuroleptic malignant syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever, autonomic instability, and altered mental status. However, it requires exposure to antipsychotic medications and typically presents with lead-pipe rigidity rather than choreiform movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstance-induced psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the history of no recreational drug use. While some substances can cause both psychiatric and autonomic symptoms, the progressive nature and neurological features are more consistent with autoimmune encephalitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute schizophrenia\u003C/strong\u003E would not account for the movement disorders, autonomic instability, or decreased level of consciousness. While schizophrenia can present with positive symptoms (delusions and hallucinations), the presence of significant neurological findings suggests an alternative diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-NMDA receptor encephalitis predominantly affects young women and may be associated with ovarian teratomas. The condition typically progresses from psychiatric symptoms to neurological manifestations including movement disorders, autonomic instability, and decreased level of consciousness. Early recognition is crucial as prompt treatment with immunotherapy can improve outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis often presents with psychiatric symptoms that can mimic first episode psychosis.","Movement disorders, autonomic instability, and decreased level of consciousness are key features that distinguish anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis from primary psychiatric disorders.","Young women are at highest risk of anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis, which may be associated with ovarian teratomas."],"references":["Endres D, Rauer S, Kern W, Venhoff N, Maier SJ, Runge K, S\u00fc\u00df P, Feige B, Nickel K, Heidt T, Domschke K. Psychiatric presentation of anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis. Frontiers in neurology. 2019 Nov 5;10:1086."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48442"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15879"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48442"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T14:31:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T14:36:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8570"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62991"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"